A message from Otsego County:

DAYCARE NEEDS SURVEY for Otsego County Residents

Otsego County officials are working with several other agencies to determine daycare needs for this year's K-12 school year. To have a better understanding of the needs, we have created a quick survey residents of Otsego County can fill out.
We will review the results of this survey to see if we can do anything to assist residents with daycare needs. If you have school-aged children, please fill this survey out before Thursday, August 27th, 2020. Thank you.

https://www.surveymonkey.com/r/GPX3J5Q

post_text: WCS completed the 14th and final week of distributing breakfast and lunches to our students. Joe Calleja, Michele Wright, and Steve Fancher assembled the food bundles. Misty Blanchard delivered food every week. Tom Hunt, Eric Haley, Annette Southworth, and Dawn Tuthill also delivered food at various times. In addition, Mr. Gonzales came every Sunday to help distribute and load the cars. Thank you to everyone for all of your help with this!  #wcspride #wcsstrong

post_text:
Here is a summer reading message from Mrs. Cody, our Librarian:

Don't forget that you can access the Library web pages all summer long. There are many resources that you can access to keep having summer reading fun. There are several links for Scholastic resources, Summer reading through New York State activities and online book links. And you can still use SORA using your lunch number and the password read.

Another way you can continue learning over the summer is using the databases.
If you liked the questions that I posted last week, you can access them yourselves by going to Elementary Gale in Context in the SEEK databases. They post an "I wonder" question that you can use to learn something new everyday. Remember you need to use the username Worcester and password "look" to access the databases. You can access this all summer long so Keep On Learning!

post_text:
A note from Miss Louis, our elementary counselor:

"How can we maintain predictability, consistency and sense of belonging? Given the stress and the potentially traumatic impact of the COVID-19 crisis, predictable and consistent routines are critically important in helping students feel calm and comfort in the face of stress. Providing a structure that enables students to know when their teacher will be available to them can be a lifesaver for many children. Knowing that there will continue to be an opportunity to interact with peers online can be exciting and energizing for students, solidifying their sense of belonging and their enthusiasm about returning to the school community when the crisis is over."

See the link below for more on helping our students strive, support, succeed.

https://traumasensitiveschools.org/trauma-sensitive-remote-learning-maintaining-predictability-consistency-and-belonging/

TRAUMASENSITIVESCHOOLS.ORG

post_text:
As you know Governor Andrew Cuomo has announced that New York school facilities will remain closed for the remainder of the 2019-20 academic year. As we look to the future, we must think about what a return to school buildings might look like and how best to support students, families and staff.

We know that we are stronger together and need all voices to be heard on this important matter. Please participate in a statewide virtual conversation about reopening schools. You will be able to read and rate other participants' responses. Based on those ratings, the most important thoughts will rise to the top. All contributions are anonymous.

This is a statewide exchange facilitated by the 37 New York BOCES (Boards of Cooperative Educational Services). The exchange results will be shared with our elected officials so that they will have a more global understanding of the thoughts and ideas our community members have about returning to in-person schooling.

Thought Exchange Link: https://my.thoughtexchange.com/333518046

Mrs. Cody, our Librarian, would like to share these resources that families can use to listen to stories online:

LeVar Burton Reads #LeVarBurtonReads
Former Reading Rainbow host
Burton says he plans to host three LeVar Burton Reads sessions a week on Twitter (at @levarburton): Mondays at 9 a.m. PT will be childrens selections; Wednesdays at 3 p.m. PT will be for young-adult audiences; and Fridays at 6 p.m. PT are for adults. https://twitter.com/levarburton?ref_src=twsrc%5Egoogle%7Ctwcamp%5Eserp%7Ctwgr%5Eauthor

Mrs. P reads stories to children. A wide variety of classic stories as well as activities such as making bookmarks and books.
http://mrsp.com/

Storyline Online Great classic stories read by famous people with information about how long the story is, grade level, reader and author. Find a great book to enjoy!
https://www.storylineonline.net

post_text: Thank you so much to our students and their families, as well as our community members who stood outside waving and greeting our parade today with wonderful signs and warm smiles (even if the weather didnt cooperate 100%)! We also appreciate how many staff members joined in on the fun! Our WCS staff needed this uplift as much as our students did. We love you all! We also wanted to thank NYS Trooper Ally Yeates and Sheriff Deputy Craig Morrison for participating as well. In addition, a huge shout out goes to Eric Haley for planning our routes, Tom Hunt for his assistance, and to Misty Blanchard, Dawn Tuthill, and Annette Southworth for leading us in their buses! We apologize if we missed you on our routes today as we tried our best to see all of our students. We miss you all and hope to see you soon! #wcspride

post_text:
Ms. Louis would like to share this resource that she found with you all:
#COVIBOOK
Supporting and reassuring children around the world
Dear families and educators all over the world,
I have created this short book to support and reassure our children, under the age of 7, regarding the COVID-19. This book is an invitation for families to discuss the full range of emotions arising from the current situation. It is important to point out that this resource does not seek to be a source of scientific information, but rather a tool based on fantasy. My recommendation is to print this material so children can draw on it. Remember that emotions are processed through repetitive play and stories read multiple times. Share COVIBOOK and help ease kiddo's anxiety all over the world.
With love,
Manuela Molina - the author

PDF of the book: https://660919d3-b85b-43c3-a3ad-3de6a9d37099.filesusr.com/ugd/64c685_319c5acf38d34604b537ac9fae37fc80.pdf

Link to the author's page: https://www.mindheart.co/descargables

May 16, 2019 at 7:00 PM 路

Yesterday, the Worcester PTO, the Worcester Pride Club and the Worcester Sports Booster Club came together to show our appreciation for the AWESOME staff and teachers of WCS. We received the following information from the New York State Education Department:

"In light of reports of technical difficulties, the New York State Education Department (NYSED) has postponed the Computer Based Testing (CBT) for students in grades 3-8, for tomorrow, Wednesday, April 3rd. All classes will resume as regularly scheduled. An updated testing schedule will be provided when it becomes available."

We will share with you updated information as we hear more! Thank you for your flexibility and understanding!

post_text: Roy has been selected as a finalist for this week's "Artist of the Week" award for the 4th - 6th age group. The "Artist of the Week" will be featured on the Artsonia homepage and will receive a commemorative plaque from Artsonia. In addition, Blick Art Materials has generously donated $100 gift certificates to the winning schools and $50 to the winning artists. Good luck Roy!
